('https://earthly.dev/blog/earthly-v0-6/', 'Announcing Earthly v0.6', 'Vlad A. Ionescu', 'ci, build, helps, cache, announcing, docker, v06, builds, execute, earthly, run', 'Announcing Earthly v0.6We are pleased to announce the release of Earthly v0.6 - our 80th release to date!\nEarthly is the standard foundational build layerThe #1 reason people use Earthly today is to be able to reproduce CI builds locally.\nWith Earthly v0.6 and the newly GA’d feature WITH DOCKER , Earthly can execute any number of containers in parallel, via an isolated Docker daemon that it starts up within.\nToday WITH DOCKER becomes GA.FROM earthly/dind:alpine earthly/dind:alpine WITH DOCKER \\ --load kvserver:latest=+kvserver-docker \\ --load kv-py-client:latest=+kvclient-docker \\ --load kv-rb-client:latest=+kv-ruby-client-docker RUN \\ docker run -d kvserver:latest && \\ docker run kv-py-client:latest python3 client.py fish=salmon && \\ docker run kv-py-client:latest python3 client.py fish | grep salmon && \\ docker run kv-rb-client:latest ruby client.rb fish | grep salmon ENDTo get started with integration testing head over to Earthly’s integration testing guide.\nIn Earthly v0.6 we’ve also GA’d cross-platform building, where Earthly will use QEMU to execute parts of the build that are designed for non-native platforms.', '2021-12-02', 'https://earthly.dev/blog/generated/assets/images/earthly-v0-6/header-800-a5af77046.jpg', 'earthly.dev'),
('https://edwest.substack.com/p/why-the-woke-are-the-new-victorians', 'Why the Woke are the new Victorians', 'Ed West', 'moral, ago, children, sort, generation, young, world, men, woke, victorians, far, age', 'Today we are faced with a strange new situation, though, where the young are far more sober than us.\nRather than describe us as Generation X and Zoomers, it might be more accurate, as Tom Holland suggested, to talk of Regency men and New Victorians.\nThe Factory Act of 1833 limited child labour because the nanny state fanatics said it was ‘cruel’ to send young children into dangerous mills and mines.\nThe Victorians were also quite ‘sex-negative’, and that era saw the emergence of fun-sounding groups like the Society for the Suppression of Vice.\nThe new Victorians may preach about different sins, but the sanctimony is the same.', '2021-12-03', 'https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1200,c_limit,f_jpg,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fb2cb0fe2-2e2e-4a3b-93fd-8cf1119825fe_2926x2041.jpeg', 'edwest.substack.com'),
('https://eighteenthelephant.com/2021/11/29/pushed-around-by-stars/', 'Pushed around by stars', 'View All Posts Raghuveer Parthasarathy, Published By, Raghuveer Parthasarathy, Physics Professor At The University Of Oregon', 'pushed, send, sent, share, email, nameyour, blog, check, try, posts, failed, stars', 'Send to Email AddressYour NameYour Email AddressPost was not sent - check your email addresses!\nEmail check failed, please try againSorry, your blog cannot share posts by email.', '2021-11-29', 'https://eighteenthelephant.files.wordpress.com/2021/11/glacier_27nov2021.jpg?w=1200', 'eighteenthelephant.com'),
('https://embedded.substack.com/p/instagram-is-facebook-now', 'Instagram is Facebook now', 'Kate Lindsay, Kyle Chayka, Paris Chanel, C.Hill', 'app, started, facebook, instagram, thats, content, feed, im, follow, reels', 'I’m getting almost as much content that I didn’t choose to see as content I did, and that is not Instagram.\nThat’s Facebook.\nInstagram and Facebook are of course both part of the same company, Meta, and so I guess it was inevitable that this day would come.\nAs Casey Lewis of After School recently told me, “I feel like [how] when I was just out of college I had to be on Facebook because that\'s sort of where people\'s birthdays were, Instagram is sort of that for [Gen Z], where they don\'t really want to.” And Instagram knows this.\nWhich is I guess why I’m confused that they’ve opted for the same strategy that made Facebook a boomer breeding ground.', '2021-12-03', 'https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_1200,c_limit,f_jpg,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff396af64-dc5c-47fb-9833-4f24df4968e5_822x1314.png', 'embedded.substack.com'),
('https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond_open_access', 'Diamond open access', '', 'access, study, journals, commercial, publishing, diamond, noncommercial, oa, model, open', 'Alternative labels include platinum open access, non-commercial open access, cooperative open access or, more recently, open access commons.\nTom Wilson introduced the expression \"Platinum Open Access\" in 2007 following an heated debate with Stevan Harnad and other open access activists on the American Scientist Open Access Forum mailing list.\n[18]The term \"diamond open access\" was coined later in 2012 by Marie Farge, a French mathematician and physicist and open access activist.\n[33] In 2013, Fuchs and Sandoval already noted that, as a far as the number of individual journals is concerned, Diamond open access is the main form of open access publishing: \"Diamond open access is not just an idea, but rather, as the empirical data provided in this paper shows, the dominant reality of open access[34]\".\n[58]Recognition [ edit ]While they make up for a large share of open access publications, Diamond open access journals have long been overlooked by scientific policies and funding mechanisms:This reality is however not enough acknowledged and taken into account in the open access journal debate.', '2021-12-03', 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Open_Access_colours_Venn.png/1200px-Open_Access_colours_Venn.png', 'en.wikipedia.org'),
('https://engineering.princeton.edu/news/2021/11/29/researchers-shrink-camera-size-salt-grain', 'Princeton University School of Engineering and Applied Science', '', 'university, engineering, metasurface, optical, produce, images, science, system, princeton, school, applied, camera, light, cameras, design', 'Now, researchers at Princeton University and the University of Washington have overcome these obstacles with an ultracompact camera the size of a coarse grain of salt.\nAside from a bit of blurring at the edges of the frame, the nano-sized camera’s images were comparable to those of the traditional lens setup, which is more than 500,000 times larger in volume.\nColburn conducted the work as a Ph.D. student at the University of Washington Department of Electrical & Computer Engineering (UW ECE), where he is now an affiliate assistant professor.\nHe also directs system design at Tunoptix, a Seattle-based company that is commercializing metasurface imaging technologies.\nBesides Tseng, Colburn, Whitehead, Majumdar and Heide, the study’s authors include Luocheng Huang, a Ph.D. student at the University of Washington; and Seung-Hwan Baek, a postdoctoral research associate at Princeton.', '2021-11-29', 'https://engineering.princeton.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Slide5-scaled.jpeg', 'engineering.princeton.edu'),
('https://erdaltoprak.com/apple-music-is-the-last-library-focused-music-service/', 'Apple Music is the last library focused music service', '', 'local, music, streaming, apple, based, library, features, previous, trend, services, songs, service, focused', '30.11.2021 — Music, Apple, Thoughts — 2 min readBack in the days my parents used to listen to cassette tapes and they had this huge custom cassette shelf that my father built.\nYou could buy songs, import existing ones and customize, albeit not very ergonomically, your entire library.\nNowadays we are all familiar with the various music services, the catalogue is almost the same, your choice is based essentially on additional features like the ecosystem, lyrics or family pricing.\nLet\'s get back to iTunes or rather Apple Music.\nWith the launch of their music streaming service, Apple tried to include their previous customer with features like iTunes Match and the ability to still organize your library even if you only use their streaming catalogue.', '2021-12-03', 'https://erdaltoprak.com/static/f72275ef32df6fb152d83de727b78ef5/a6c62/daniel-schludi-unsplash.jpg', 'erdaltoprak.com'),
('https://erikbern.com/2021/11/30/storm-in-the-stratosphere-how-the-cloud-will-be-reshuffled.html', 'Storm in the stratosphere: how the cloud will be reshuffled', 'Erik Bernhardsson', 'think, vendor, reshuffled, stratosphere, aws, layer, redshift, money, vendors, software, world, storm, cloud', 'Storm in the stratosphere: how the cloud will be reshuffledHere\'s a theory I have about cloud vendors (AWS, Azure, GCP):Cloud vendors will increasingly focus on the lowest layers in the stack: basically leasing capacity in their data centers through an API.\nWe currently have cloud vendors that offer end-to-end solutions from the developer experience down to the hardware:What if cloud vendors focus on the lowest layer, and other (pure software) vendors on the layer above?\nSoftware vendors can build for all the cloud vendors at the same time.\nIt\'s not like you can just pick whichever cloud vendor has the cheapest database and run your DB there.\nWe will see a lot of partnerships between startups and cloud vendors, where a cloud vendor may concede an area and try to be a preferred partner with a startup instead.', '2021-11-30', 'https://erikbern.com/assets/face.jpeg', 'erikbern.com'),
('https://event-driven.io/en/event_streaming_is_not_event_sourcing/', 'Event Streaming is not Event Sourcing!', 'Oskar Dudycz', 'streaming, youre, events, read, write, article, state, event, stores, sourcing', 'They’re not tools for Event Sourcing, but Event Streaming.\nThat’s again a difference between Event Streaming and Event Sourcing.\nEvent Sourcing and Event Streaming are different patterns that happen to integrate with each other.\nThis is not the issue of Event Sourcing or event stores per se, but using the wrong tool for the job.\nIf this article was titled ” Event Sourcing is hard if you’re confusing it with Event Streaming”, then it’d be an excellent article.', '2021-12-03', 'https://event-driven.io/static/56f85bf712e80a68e0b161404a4f9717/2a4de/2021-12-01-cover.png', 'event-driven.io'),
('https://explainthispaper.com/pages/', 'ExplainThisPaper', '', 'strange, explainthispaper, trivially, shows, work, white, thisthe, ai, xray, try, someones', 'arXivThis paper shows how AI can trivially learn to detect someone\'s race from lots of different imaging modalities (including a black and white chest X-ray).\nThis is strange, because not even expert doctors can do this.\nThe authors ran a number of experiments to try and work out how the AI is doing…', '2021-12-03', 'http://explainthispaper.com/static/img/card_img.074d730f7386.jpg', 'explainthispaper.com'),
('https://federicoterzi.com/blog/why-electron-is-a-necessary-evil/', 'Why Electron is a Necessary Evil', 'Federico Terzi', 'qt, approach, native, crossplatform, apps, library, dont, electron, necessary, applications, evil, mb', 'Over time, I developed the idea that Electron is a necessary evil, something that is (surprisingly) superior to the alternatives for many use-cases.\n: Shipping with a full Chromium runtime, you can expect most Electron apps to consume at least 150 MB of storage.\nSlow : Some Electron apps are definitely slow, but that can depend on many factors.\n: Some Electron apps are definitely slow, but that can depend on many factors.\nOf course, there are some very bloated Electron apps out there and I don’t like them either, but that’s mostly due to careless developers, not Electron.', '2021-01-21', 'https://federicoterzi.com/assets/images/Electron.png', 'federicoterzi.com'),
('https://foreignpolicy.com/2021/11/24/nature-person-rights-environment-climate-philosophy-law/', 'Nature Is Becoming a Person', 'Justin E. H. Smith, R. Maxwell Bone, Ashley Jackson, Charles Dunst, Danielle Pletka, Jack Losh, Laurie Garrett, Paul Musgrave, Brian Klaas, Natalia Antonova', 'person, legal, nonhuman, right, personhood, rivers, nature, human, law, rights', 'The expansion of the concept of “person” was perhaps always inevitable.\nLegislation in Bolivia, and indeed Ecuador’s new 2008 constitution, enshrine within law the “rights of nature.” While being a rights-bearer is not precisely the same thing as being a person, the two have typically overlapped to the point of near co-extensivity throughout modern history.\nSaying a given good, such as clean water, is a “human right” lends gravity to arguments for government funding of sanitation plants or deeper wells.\nWe may thus still ask whether the personalization of nature is only a useful fiction enshrined into law.\nA natural person for Hobbes, again, is someone who speaks for him or herself; an artificial person is someone who speaks for another, whether that be another individual person or any other entity or collection of entities.', '2021-11-24', 'https://foreignpolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/GettyImages-1204312438.jpg?w=1000', 'foreignpolicy.com'),
('https://freddiev4.xyz/solving-advent-of-code-puzzles-with-github-copilot/', 'Solving Advent of Code Puzzles with GitHub Copilot: Day 1', 'Freddie Vargus', 'copilot, array, solving, day, sum, measurements, puzzles, code, data, github, depth_list, advent', 'Solving Advent of Code Puzzles with GitHub Copilot: Day 1WARNING: Spoilers for Advent of Code belowThis year, I decided to try my hand at solving Advent of Code puzzles, mostly out of curiosity since I know this advent calendar has been around for several years, and I wanted to see what it was all about.\nIf you’re not familiar with Advent of Code, essentially it’s an advent calendar that has programming puzzles each day that you’re meant to solve, with a web page to which you submit answers.\nPuzzle OneSo I started by copying a piece of the advent day 1 puzzle description (the first puzzle):# count the number of times a depth measurement increases from the previous measurement.\nI’ve embedded a video below:And here’s the code Copilot came up with in text format:# count the number of times a depth measurement increases from the previous measurement.\nI’ll post an update on day 2 or day 3 of the Advent of Code and also try to use more of the puzzle description rather than sentences I think are the most useful for the Copilot program.', '2021-12-01', 'https://freddiev4.github.io/assets/images/', 'freddiev4.xyz'),
('https://gcc.gnu.org/wiki/DontUseInlineAsm', 'DontUseInlineAsm', '', 'compilers, dontuseinlineasm, c, using, asm, different, inline, code, specific, gccs, reasons', 'Even for people experienced in working with gcc\'s inline asm, it can be very tricky to get things exactly right.\nWhen your application is ported to another platform, the inline asm will need to be re-written, not just re-compiled (as the C code can be).\nThere are no C standards that define the semantics of inline asm, so different compilers can and do handle it differently.\nUsing inline asm disables the compiler\'s ability to compute constant values.\nIt might make more sense to write a wrapper in assembly that performs the necessary translation instead of using inline asm.', '2021-12-03', '', 'gcc.gnu.org'),
('https://gigablast.com/about.html', 'Gigablast', '', 'search, turn, index, partner, gigablast, topic, united, variety, wells, information', 'Founded in 2000, Matt Wells created Gigablast to index hundreds of billions of pages with the least amount of hardware possible.\nGigablast provides large-scale, high-performance, real-time information retrieval technology and services for partner sites.\nThis search delivery mechanism gives a partner \"turn key\" search capability and the capacity to instantly offer search at maximum scalability with minimum cost.\nGigablast is one of a handful of search engines in the United States that maintains its own searchable index of over a billion pages.\nFor more information, contact Gigablast.', '2021-12-03', '', 'gigablast.com'),
