('https://github.com/jes/scamp-cpu', 'jes/scamp-cpu: A homebrew 16-bit CPU with a homebrew Unix-like-ish operating system.', '', 'unixlikeish, ___, compactflash, write, operating, cpu, __, _, system, homebrew, 16bit, memory, jesscampcpu, run', 'SCAMP CPUSCAMP is my homebrew 16-bit CPU.\nIt runs a homebrew operating system, with a homebrew programming language and compiler, and can self-host the kernel and all of the system utilities.\nThe bus is 16-bit, registers are 16-bit, addresses are 16-bit, and memory contents are 16-bit.\nSCAMP boot... .......................................................OK starting kernel... loading init... ____ ____ _ __ __ ____ __ / ___| / ___| / \\ | \\/ | _ \\ / /__ ___ \\___ \\| | / _ \\ | |\\/| | |_) / / _ \\/ __| ___) | |___ / ___ \\| | | | __/ / (_) \\__ \\ |____/ \\____/_/ \\_\\_| |_|_| /_/ \\___/|___/ $If you know how to use Unix you\'ll probably understand how to use it.\nSCAMP is featured on the Homebrew CPU ring which also features many other interesting homebrew CPU designs.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/893118402eb3781cec1800b5f87f8d01d3a6910f5b62bd9ad5cd86df2641bc7f/jes/scamp-cpu', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/jesseduffield/horcrux', 'jesseduffield/horcrux: Split your file into encrypted fragments so that you don\'t need to remember a passcode', '', 'resurrect, horcrux, original, key, directory, fragments, need, passcode, file, jesseduffieldhorcrux, dont, horcruxes, remember, split, encrypted', 'horcruxSplit your file into encrypted horcruxes so that you don\'t need to remember a passcodeHow it workshorcrux has two commands, split and bind .\nSplittingIf I have a file called diary.txt in my current directory I can callhorcrux split diary.txtand it will prompt me for how many horcruxes I want, and how many will be needed to resurrect the original file.\nFor example I might want 5 horcruxes with the ability to resurrect the file if I have any 3.\nBindingTo bind the horcruxes back into the original file just callhorcrux bindin the directory containing the horcruxes (or pass the directory as an argument).\nA) This uses the Shamir Secret Sharing Scheme to break an encryption key into parts that can be recombined to create the original key, but only requiring a certain threshold to do so.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/348aecdf5f3dfb8a376e1d6489497389949ac33ea9e604bb0ca50981074d044a/jesseduffield/horcrux', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/jesseduffield/lazydocker', 'jesseduffield/lazydocker: The lazier way to manage everything docker', '', 'logs, build, lazydocker, way, install, dockercompose, lazier, jesseduffieldlazydocker, terminal, buildarg, lazyteamlazydocker, service, manage, docker', 'A simple terminal UI for both docker and docker-compose, written in Go with the gocui library.\nTap:brew install jesseduffield/lazydocker/lazydockerCore:brew install lazydockerScoop (Windows)You can install lazydocker using scoop:scoop install lazydockerChocolatey (Windows)You can install lazydocker using Chocolatey:choco install lazydockerYou can install asdf-lazydocker plugin using asdf-vm:Setup (Once)asdf plugin add lazydocker https://github.com/comdotlinux/asdf-lazydocker.gitFor Install / Upgradeasdf list all lazydocker asdf install lazydocker 0.12 asdf global lazydocker 0.12Binary Release (Linux/OSX/Windows)You can manually download a binary release from the release page.\nIf you encounter a compatibility issue with Docker bundled binary, try rebuilding the image with the build argument --build-arg DOCKER_VERSION=\"v$(docker -v | cut -d\" \" -f3 | rev | cut -c 2- | rev)\" so that the bundled docker binary matches your host docker binary version.\nBy default we only show logs from the last hour, so that we\'re not putting too much strain on the machine.\nThis can be overwritten in the config\'s commandTemplatesIf you are running lazydocker in Docker container, it is a know bug, that you can\'t see logs or CPU usage.', '2021-12-03', 'https://repository-images.githubusercontent.com/187335810/d5cecc00-9b1c-11e9-8abf-5649b23bce13', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/jesseduffield/lazygit', 'jesseduffield/lazygit: simple terminal UI for git commands', '', 'ui, sudo, simple, youre, add, git, linux, commands, install, jesseduffieldlazygit, lazygit, terminal, file, zshrc, available', 'A simple terminal UI for git commands, written in Go with the gocui library.\nRant time: You\'ve heard it before, git is powerful, but what good is that power when everything is so damn hard to do?\nThe stable one which is built with the latest release and the git version which builds from the most recent commit.\nChocolatey (Windows)You can install lazygit using Chocolatey:choco install lazygitManualYou\'ll need to install Gogit clone https://github.com/jesseduffield/lazygit.git cd lazygit go installYou can also use go run main.go to compile and run in one go (pun definitely intended)UsageCall lazygit in your terminal inside a git repository.\n$ lazygitIf you want, you can also add an alias for this with echo \"alias lg=\'lazygit\'\" >> ~/.zshrc (or whichever rc file you\'re using).', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/1aee46c23c634a449f1f894018ba663bbc06997e193ac6a13d69165f304b3d9d/jesseduffield/lazygit', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/lepoco/wpfui', 'lepoco/wpfui: A simple way to make your application written in WPF keep up with modern design trends.', '', 'add, written, simple, lepocowpfui, wpfuicontrols, grid, window, application, design, resourcedictionary, trends, wpf, icons, modern, way, windows, navigation, source', 'WPF UICreated with ❤ in Poland by lepo.coA simple way to make your application written in WPF keep up with modern design trends.\nCardProfile WPFUI.Controls Simple element that displays an image in a circular frame like in default applications for Windows 11.\nNavigation WPFUI.Controls Navigation styled as UWP apps.\nNavigationStore WPFUI.Controls Navigation styled as Windows 11 Store app NavigationFluent WPFUI.Controls Navigation styled as Windows 11 Settings app.\nTitleBar WPFUI.Controls A set of buttons that can replace the default window navigation, giving it a new, modern look.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/b50a05e609518789da762d4a41e28a0f3ff6b80ced67d2cbdbb57d56080b820d/lepoco/wpfui', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/mrthefakeperson/Excel-Virtual-Machine', 'mrthefakeperson/Excel-Virtual-Machine: C Compiler which targets Excel (MS Office)', '', 'io, excel_vm, office, c, excel, currently, microsoft, ms, version, mrthefakepersonexcelvirtualmachine, file, compiler, targets, myfilefile, project, standard', 'PurposeThis project aims to accurately compile common programming languages and I/O features into Microsoft Excel (2015) files.\nFrom the latest release version: use the command Excel_VM myFile.file -outputExcelFile (or Excel_VM myFile.file to get a Windows compatible executable file), replacing myFile.file with the name of your file.\nThe compiled Excel file can be executed by triggering iterative calculation (pressing F9 repeatedly) in Microsoft Excel.\nThe project currently supports C and F# (incomplete).\nI/O operations are supported with cell A2 acting as standard input, and cell B2 acting as standard output.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/74dd2f8a9399e8bd72f8e21500480bc5c4688b8aff07a3df1e44a81aedc3ab39/mrthefakeperson/Excel-Virtual-Machine', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/phantomics/april', 'phantomics/april: The APL programming language (a subset thereof) compiling to Common Lisp.', '', 'apl, workspace, space1, programming, language, subset, common, functions, state, phantomicsapril, code, compiling, output, lisp, function, aprilf, thereof', 'APL Functions and OperatorsThe APL language uses single characters to represent its primitive functions and operators.\nSome APL functions and operators won\'t be added to April since they don\'t make sense for April\'s design as a compiler from APL to Lisp.\nKeep in mind that standard Common Lisp functions like + do not operate on entire arrays like APL functions do.\nFor example, to clear a workspace called space1 , enter:* (april-clear-workspace space1) \" The workspace ｢SPACE1｣ has been cleared. \"\nLoading Code Directly From FilesPerhaps you\'d like to write files containing pure APL code rather than passing strings to (april) within Lisp code.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/77ee4422c6362da506e1f21d6a1d124543b4ed54306b1a21fa48beff11524966/phantomics/april', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/r1mikey/research-unix-v7', 'r1mikey/research-unix-v7: Research UNIX v7 ported the the Raspberry Pi', '', 'v7, unix, qemu, sync, card, raspberry, sd, r1mikeyresearchunixv7, partition, pi, code, ported, l, research, mode', 'Research UNIX v7 for Raspberry PiThis repository contains a port of AT&T Research UNIX v7 to the Raspberry Pi 1 single-board computer.\nThe code is expected to gracefully degrade to a single-CPU experience on later Raspberry Pi models, up the the Pi 3.\nUNIX Code Copyrights and Ownership:The UNIX v7 codebase is covered under the Caldera License Grant.\nWhile much of the port code is original work, portions originate in from other open-source projects:Recommended ReadingPreparing an SD Card and ImagemacOSInsert an SD card (even a 512MiB card is sufficient).\nTo do so, leave multi-user mode, ensure all disk buffers are flushed, then exit (the same applies to qemu):kill -1 1 sync && sync && sync && sync && echo safe # remove power nowContributingPlease feel free to hack away on this code.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/4d98cbef3bb6e714a70ce919b872d06034f6d77118d39a7c6edf431a63ff798b/r1mikey/research-unix-v7', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/RumbleDB/rumble', 'Run queries on your large-scale, messy JSON-like data (JSON, text, CSV, Parquet, ROOT, AVRO, SVM...)', '', 'documentation, jupyter, parquet, root, text, language, messy, largescale, lot, queries, validate, query, json, jsonlike, available, svm, rumbledb, data, run', 'RumbleDBWith RumbleDB, you can query with ease a lot of different nested, heterogeneous data formats like JSON, CSV, Parquet, Avro, LibSVM, text, etc.\nRumbleDB exposes a query language rather than a DataFrame API, for more flexibility, more productivity but also because a lot of data simply will not fit in DataFrames.\nYou can query it in place from any local file systems or data lakes (Azure blob storage, Amazon S3, HDFS, etc).\nYou can prepare, clean up, validate your data and put it right into your machine learning pipelines with RumbleDB ML.\nGetting started: you will find a Jupyter notebook that introduces the JSONiq language on top of RumbleDB here.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/25d7a20f2dd7351d026f43f518661b4addf0a812a03c517fa7279f768db5ea6d/RumbleDB/rumble', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/securitykiss-com/csp', 'securitykiss-com/csp: Tcl library for Golang style concurrency based on Communicating Sequential Processes', '', 'style, securitykisscomcsp, receiving, library, based, coroutines, communicating, sending, named, csp, sequential, concurrency, tcl, pipes, processes, waiting, golang', 'csp - Golang inspired concurrency library for TclThe csp package for Tcl is a concurrency library based on Communicating Sequential Processes and provides two primitives namely coroutines and channels which allow concurrent programming in the style of Golang.\nThe concepts originate in Hoare\'s Communicating Sequential Processes while the syntax mimics the Golang implementation.\nThe CSP concurrency model may be visualized as a set of independent processes (coroutines) sending and receiving messages to the named channels.\nThe control flow in the coroutines is coordinated at the points of sending and receiving messages i.e.\nThis concurrency model may also be seen as a generalization of Unix named pipes where processes and pipes correspond to coroutines and channels.', '2021-12-03', 'https://opengraph.githubassets.com/83e709c3088bc635fe2243aca7c268d2be821bd73aaa11dcd79f34ef07608f9c/securitykiss-com/csp', 'github.com'),
('https://github.com/supabase/supabase/tree/master/studio', 'supabase/studio at master · supabase/supabase', '', 'master, youre, supabase, supabasestudio, following, supabasesupabase, npm, selfhosted, pr, dashboard, dockercompose, studio, run', 'Supabase StudioA dashboard for managing your self-hosted Supabase project, and used on our hosted platform.\nIf you\'re planning to contribute, it is advised that you run git pull frequently to retrieve the latest updates.\nIf you\'re deploying Supabase to your own cloud, you should store your secrets and env vars in a vault or secrets manager.\ncd .. cd docker docker-compose upOnce you\'ve got that set up, update .env in the studio folder with the corresponding values.\nPOSTGRES_PASSWORD= SUPABASE_ANON_KEY= SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY=Then run the follow commands to install dependencies and start the dashboard.', '2021-12-03', 'https://repository-images.githubusercontent.com/214587193/00f59f00-90a6-11eb-8764-f49e3f731458', 'github.com'),
('https://gitlab.tue.nl/20040367/pybaobab', 'Elzen, Stef van den / pybaobab', '', 'elzen, pybaobab, den, stef, van', '', '2021-12-03', 'https://gitlab.tue.nl/assets/gitlab_logo-7ae504fe4f68fdebb3c2034e36621930cd36ea87924c11ff65dbcb8ed50dca58.png', 'gitlab.tue.nl'),
('https://gizmodo.com/crime-prediction-software-promised-to-be-free-of-biases-1848138977', 'PredPol Crime Predictions Target Poor, Blacks, Latinos', 'Aaron Sankin, Dhruv Mehrotra, Surya Mattu, Dell Cameron, Annie Gilbertson, Daniel Lempres, Josh Lash', 'city, latino, neighborhoods, crime, poor, policing, predpol, crimes, predictions, target, software, latinos, data, blacks', 'Crimes were predicted every day, sometimes multiple times a day, sometimes in multiple locations in the same neighborhood: thousands upon thousands of crime predictions over years.\nAdvertisementWe found the crime predictions for our analysis through a link on the Los Angeles Police Department’s public website, which led to an open cloud storage bucket containing PredPol predictions for not just the LAPD but also for dozens of other departments.\nThe algorithm uses three variables to come up with future crime predictions: the date and time, the location, and the type of past crime reports.\n“We use crime data as reported to the police by the victims themselves,” he said.\nFerguson, the American University professor, said that whatever PredPol’s future, crime predictions made by software are here to stay—though not necessarily as a standalone product.', '2021-12-03', 'https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fill,f_auto,fl_progressive,g_center,h_675,pg_1,q_80,w_1200/1ac9c621675f4aaee384ba5c79bdf6b8.png', 'gizmodo.com'),
('https://gizmodo.com/what-could-be-cooler-than-typing-on-a-keyboard-salvaged-1848148657', 'What Could Be Cooler Than Typing on a Keyboard Salvaged From a Nuclear Missile Silo?', '', 'react, iii, nuclear, cooler, air, missile, silo, trackball, forces, salvaged, keyboard, typing, minuteman, hardware', 'Knowing the history of their hardware is often as important to keyboard enthusiasts as the feel and sounds of the keys they’re pounding away on all day.\nBut it’s hard to imagine a keyboard having a more interesting backstory than this bizarre layout that was salvaged from a Minuteman III nuclear missile silo.\nThat was three decades ago, however, and the hardware used in the Minuteman III nuclear missile silos has been updated again, but instead of sending the REACT consoles to the junkyard , in true capitalist fashion, some of them ended up on eBay.\nThe first USB ports only started showing up in computers around 1998, and there was little chance it was available in time for the Air Force’s new REACT consoles which undoubtedly took years to design and develop before being implemented.\nOn top of that, custom software had to be developed to get both devices to play nice with something other than computers designed to launch nuclear missiles, and that can be downloaded here if you happen to come across a Minuteman III REACT console to call your own but don’t have a nuclear missile silo to go with it.', '2021-12-03', 'https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fill,f_auto,fl_progressive,g_center,h_675,pg_1,q_80,w_1200/6880074ffe6497ed45fab2592b257103.jpg', 'gizmodo.com'),
('https://gizmodo.com/zooms-new-attendance-tool-will-snitch-on-attendees-who-1848150339', 'Zoom\'s New Attendance Tool Will Snitch on Attendees Who Are Late to a Meeting', '', 'attendance, status, participants, zoom, late, students, way, calendar, tool, meeting, zooms, snitch, attendees, joined', 'Zoom is adding in a new feature that may make it more difficult for you to casually coast your way into a meeting without your boss noticing .\nThe new “Attendance Status” tool, first spotted by Tech Radar, allows Zoom hosts and co-hosts to use calendar integration from Google and Microsoft to easily see whether or not invited participants joined the meeting on time.\nAdvertisementAccording to Zoom’s support page, meeting participants who have been invited but who have not joined will be siloed into a “Not Joined” section where their names will appear alongside other lazy deplorables.\nIn order to view a participant’s status, Zoom said hosts will need to have calendar integration with Google Calendar or Outlook calendar enabled and configured.\nBut never fear fellow chronically late arrivers, there’s a potential way out thanks to a soundboard created by digital artist Sam Lavigne.', '2021-12-03', 'https://i.kinja-img.com/gawker-media/image/upload/c_fill,f_auto,fl_progressive,g_center,h_675,pg_1,q_80,w_1200/85b485bff2335a93f05b2fb3aafca78d.jpg', 'gizmodo.com'),
('https://gmplib.org/list-archives/gmp-devel/2021-September/006013.html', 'Risc V greatly underperforms', '', 'add, instructions, t1, sltu, set, t6, greatly, v, isa, risc, underperforms, instruction', 'Risc V greatly underperformsIt seems safe to assume that most people on this list have heard of Risc V by now, the license-free instruction set.\nMy conclusion is that Risc V is a terrible architecture.\nAny task will require more Risc V instructions that any contemporary instruction set.\nI believe that an average computer science student could come up with a better instruction set that Risc V in a single term project.\nLet\'s look at some examples of how Risc V underperforms.', '2021-12-03', '', 'gmplib.org'),
('https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/2021/12/this-shouldnt-have-happened.html', 'Project Zero: This shouldn\'t have happened: A vulnerability postmortem', '', 'team, zero, postmortem, updates, google, happened, shouldnt, vulnerability, project', 'News and updates from the Project Zero team at Google', '2021-12-03', 'https://googleprojectzero.blogspot.com/favicon.ico', 'googleprojectzero.blogspot.com'),
('https://hackaday.com/2021/12/01/supersonic-projectile-exceeds-engineers-dreams-the-supersonic-trebuchet/', 'Supersonic Projectile Exceeds Engineers Dreams: The Supersonic Trebuchet', 'Ryan Flowers, Terry S, Roscoe Brown, Billy Williams', 'trebuchet, dreams, supersonic, thing, video, speed, thrown, sound, exceeds, trebuchets, fast, projectile, engineers', 'Have you ever sat down and thought “I wonder if a trebuchet could launch a projectile at supersonic speeds?” Neither have we.\nThe trebuchet is a type of catapult that was popular for use as a siege engine before gunpowder became a thing.\nBut of course you’re here to read about the other thing that trebuchets can be used for: speed.\n[David]’s video explains in full all of the engineering that went into his trebuchet, and it’s a lot less than you’d think.\n[David]’s impressive project and presentation makes it clear that all one has to do to build a supersonic trebuchet is to try.', '2021-12-01', 'https://hackaday.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/supersonic-trebuchet-featured.jpg', 'hackaday.com'),
('https://haydenjames.io/linux-performance-almost-always-add-swap-space/', 'Linux Performance: Why You Should Almost Always Add Swap Space', 'Hayden James', 'performance, cache, add, server, linux, used, space, memory, ram, pages, swap', 'We know that using Linux swap space instead of RAM (memory) can severely slow down performance.\n00:00:29 kswapd0…so in this case, as in many, swap usage is not hurting Linux server performance.\nNow, let’s look at how swap space can actually help Linux server performance.\nSwap usage becomes a performance problem when the Kernel is pressured to continuously move memory pages in and out of memory and swap space.\nFor a more detailed look at Linux swap space, read the Swap Management and Page Frame Reclamation chapters from Kernel.org docs.', '2021-12-02', 'https://static.haydenjames.io/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/atop-512GB-server-868x357.png', 'haydenjames.io'),
('https://hazlitt.net/longreads/sacrifice', 'Sacrifice', '', 'man, justos, cathedral, ángel, longer, told, god, wanted, didnt, justo, sacrifice', 'It was in the midst of this incessant self-questioning, he said, that it came to him—the idea to build something for his Creator: a cathedral, which would demonstrate his willingness to sacrifice himself for God.\nNor was there much inspiration from architects, who Justo didn’t like being compared to.\nAquarius had made his faith synonymous with ambition, his devotion with perseverance, and his sacrifice with self-interest.\n“You have to read The Imitation of Christ by Thomas à Kempis,” Justo told me excitedly.\nWhen I talked to the vicar in charge of all the diocese’s architectural projects, he was cagey about Justo’s cathedral.', '2021-12-01', 'https://hazlitt.net/sites/default/files/field/image/000032380029.jpg', 'hazlitt.net'),
('https://historynewsnetwork.org/article/175506', 'A Mathematical Duel in 16th Century Venice (Excerpt)', 'Fabio Toscano Translated Arturo Sangalli', 'solved, formula, 16th, questions, tartaglia, venice, mathematical, secret, fior, problems, thirty, history, century, excerpt, duel', 'His latest book, The Secret Formula: How a Mathematical Duel Inflamed Renaissance Italy and Uncovered the Cubic Equation, will be published by Princeton University Press on May 19.\nThe Secret Formula is the story of two Renaissance mathematicians whose jealousies, intrigues, and contentious debates led to the discovery of a formula for the solution of the cubic equation.\nNiccolò Tartaglia was an ambitious teacher who possessed a secret formula – the key to unlocking a seemingly unsolvable, two-thousand-year-old mathematical problem.\nSixteenth-century mathematical duels had a long history, rigid procedures, and a lasting impact on the duelists’ standing in their communities.\nHe proposed thirty problems to Tartaglia, who in response sent the challenger thirty other questions.', '2021-12-03', 'https://historynewsnetwork.org/images/hnn-favicons/apple-icon-57x57.png', 'historynewsnetwork.org'),
('https://imagemagick.org/script/index.php', 'ImageMagick', 'Imagemagick Studio Llc', 'os, images, write, read, commandline, scripts, source, imagemagick, release, image', 'ImageMagick utilizes multiple computational threads to increase performance and can read, process, or write mega-, giga-, or tera-pixel image sizes.\nFeatures and CapabilitiesHere are just a few examples of what ImageMagick can do for you:Examples of ImageMagick Usage shows how to use ImageMagick from the command-line to accomplish any of these tasks and much more.\nAlso, see Fred\'s ImageMagick Scripts: a plethora of command-line scripts that perform geometric transforms, blurs, sharpens, edging, noise removal, and color manipulations.\nWith Magick.NET, use ImageMagick without having to install ImageMagick on your server or desktop.\nFinally, see Snibgo\'s ImageMagick Cookbook for Windows-based ImageMagick scripting.', '2021-12-03', 'https://imagemagick.org/image/logo.png', 'imagemagick.org'),
('https://julialang.org/blog/2021/11/julia-1.7-highlights/', 'Julia 1.7 Highlights', 'Jeff Bezanson, Stefan Karpinski, Viral Shah, Alan Edelman, Et Al.', 'syntax, example, highlights, package, using, 17, c, julia, b, pkg, foo, return', 'What used to bejulia> using Foo ERROR: ArgumentError: Package Foo not found in current path: - Run `import Pkg; Pkg.add(\"Foo\")` to install the Foo package.\nStacktrace: [1] require(into::Module, mod::Symbol) @ Base ./loading.jl:871 (@1.6) pkg> add Foo ... julia> using Foo julia> Foo Foocan now be achieved with justjulia> using Foo │ Package Foo not found, but a package named Foo is available from a registry.\nIt is therefore not recommended to use a manifest created in one Julia version with another Julia version.\nKristoffer CarlssonWe noticed some complaints about the speed of the Julia package manager (Pkg) on Windows and on Network File Systems (NFSs).\nThe Julia User & Developer Survey 2021 showed that 5% of Julia users were already running Julia on this platform before an official stable version for it was released!', '2021-12-03', 'https://julialang.org/assets/images/julia-open-graph.png', 'julialang.org'),
('https://karl-voit.at/2021/11/27/orgdown/', 'Orgdown - a New Lightweight Markup Standard for Text Documents', 'Karl Voit', 'syntax, text, gnuemacs, support, language, orgmode, users, standard, lightweight, orgdown, elements, documents, orgdown1, markup', 'At EmacsConf21, I announced a new standard for a lightweight markup language: Orgdown.\nOn the other hand, it refers to a lightweight markup language similar to Markdown, AsciiDoc, Wikitext or reStructuredText.\nIndependent of this, I do like the design of Org-mode markup.\nIn many online discussions, people did not seem to be able to differ between the Elisp code and the design of the markup language.\nIn the meantime, let\'s kick-start Orgdown with Orgdown1 and spread the brilliant markup design of Org-mode using Orgdown as a well-defined standard.', '2021-11-27', 'http://Karl-Voit.at/images/public-voit_T_logo_200x200.png', 'karl-voit.at'),
('https://karthinks.com/software/avy-can-do-anything/', 'Avy can do anything', '', 'text, select, avy, candidate, type, isearch, filter, avygotochartimer, jump, run', 'Avy actionsThe basic usage for running an arbitrary action with Avy is as follows:Call an Avy command.\nThe intermediate job of candidate selection is shared between Avy and Embark: Avy specifies the general location of the candidate, and Embark figures out the semantic unit at that position on which to act.\nAvy + Isearch: Seek, then jumpIsearch and Avy have different strengths: Avy jumps quickly to any visible element in any window, Isearch to any matching candidate in this buffer.\nThe smell testHowever, using Avy actions is a new way of interacting with text on your screen even if you already use Avy to jump around.\nBut Avy is composed of modular pieces that makes it suitable for a wide variety of Filter → Select applications as well.', '2021-10-21', 'https://karthinks.com/img/avy-basic-demo.png', 'karthinks.com'),
('https://knowingless.com/2021/11/27/frame-control/', 'Frame Control', '', 'maybe, feel, things, dont, bad, frame, im, really, good, control', 'Frame control is an effect; very often, people who frame control will not be aware that this is what they’re doing, and have extensive reasoning to rationalize their behavior that they themselves believe.\nI’m talking a bit philosophically about frame control, but in an attempt to get more concrete, here’s a non-exhaustive list of some frame control symptoms.\nSo if frame control looks so similar to just being a normal person, what are some signs that someone isn’t doing frame control?\nFor this reason I don’t think all frame control is inherently harmful; it’s possible, for example, to be close friends with a heavy frame controller while being fully aware of all of the frame control moves they might be doing.\nAnd people who frame control may also accuse others of frame control as a weapon for sowing self doubt (and dismiss accusations of frame control at themselves as simply weapons for sowing seeds of self doubt).', '2021-11-27', 'https://i0.wp.com/knowingless.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/cropped-knnwinglesslogo1biggerdot514.jpg?fit=512%2C512&ssl=1', 'knowingless.com'),
('https://krorgs.github.io/', 'About', '', 'combine, unique, growing, paper, clusters, work, replicate, cc, useful, cells', 'youtube | downloadAlmost all organisms replicate by growing and then shedding offspring.\nSome molecules also replicate, but by moving rather than growing: they find and combine building blocks into self copies.\nFinally, we show that AI can design clusters that replicate better, and perform useful work as they do so.\nRun, fork and modify our source code and build instructions for noncommercial purposes (CC BY-NC 4.0).\nEach of us made unique contributions to the paper, and thus have unique perspectives on the work.', '2021-12-03', 'https://krorgs.github.io/img/icon.png', 'krorgs.github.io');
