('https://proteanmag.com/2021/11/29/the-american-prison-systems-war-on-reading/', 'The American Prison System\'s War on Reading • Protean Magazine', '', 'book, free, prisons, protean, american, magazine, state, reading, systems, prisoners, states, prison, war, incarcerated, books', 'With free books banned, prisoners are forced to rely on the small list of “approved vendors” chosen for them by the prison administration.\nThe rise of these private vendors has also been mirrored by the systematic dismantling of the prison library system.\nOklahoma, meanwhile, has no dedicated budget for books at all, requiring prison librarians to purchase them out-of-pocket.\nI knew right there in prison that reading had changed forever the course of my life.\nSending free books to people in prison is one such means, and if the recent backlash against donations is anything to judge by, it’s a potent one.', '2021-11-29', 'https://proteanmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/skopic-prison-reading.jpg', 'proteanmag.com'),
('https://publicdomainreview.org/features/entering-the-public-domain/2022/', 'What Will Enter the Public Domain in 2022?', '', 'works, public, enter, countries, copyright, life, died, domain, term, plus, 2022', 'At the start of each year, on January 1st, a new crop of works enter the public domain and become free to enjoy, share, and reuse for any purpose.\nFind here, in this advent-style calendar, our top pick of what lies in store for 2022.\nDue to differing copyright laws around the world, there is no one single public domain — and here we focus on three of the most prominent.\nNewly entering the public domain in 2022 will be: works by people who died in 1951, for countries with a copyright term of “life plus 70 years” (e.g.\nUK, Russia, most of EU and South America); works by people who died in 1971, for countries with a term of “life plus 50 years” (e.g.', '2021-12-03', 'https://the-public-domain-review.imgix.net/features/countdown/2022/2022-opengraph.jpeg', 'publicdomainreview.org'),
